ard In 1967 the Licensed Clinical Social Worker Program was established In 1970 a licensing program for Educational Psychologists was added and the Board then became known as the Board of Behavioral Science Examiners On January 1 1997 the name of the Board was officially changed to Board of Behavioral Sciences to better represent its functions which extend beyond simply administering examinations The Board is composed of 11 members six public members two Licensed Clinical Social Workers one Licensed Educational Psychologist and two Licensed Marriage Family and Child Counselors Nine members are appointed by the Governor one public member is appointed by the Speaker of the Assembly and one public member is appointed by the Senate Rules Committee The Board licenses Clinical Social Workers Educational Psychologists Marriage Family and Child Counselors It registers Marriage Family and Child Counselor Interns Associate Clinical Social Workers and Continuing Education Providers The Board develops and administers written and oral examinations for its licensing programs develops regulatory standards and conducts an enforcement program which investigates consumer complaints The Board imposes disciplinary action against licensees and registrants who violate the law The Board has quarterly business meetings In addition members set aside 3 4 days each year which may be used in between Board meetings to process disciplinary decisions if necessary Effective July 1 1999 the MFCC s profession underwent a name change ie AB 1449 Brown Any reference in any statute or regulation to licensed marriage family and child counselor or marriage family and child counselor shall be deemed a reference to licensed marriage and family therapist or marriage and family therapist Effective Janaury 1 2000 the Board discontinued regulating MFT and LCSW Corporations i e AB 1667 Ch 657 However these corporations are still required to file their articles of incorporation with the California Secretary of St